Russian communism is making a comeback
MOSCOW – More than a year ago, I returned to my hometown Moscow from a sabbatical at an American university.
My destination was not a bastion of free speech.
But here, even then, there was still some freedom left.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny had toured the country trying to win support for politicians who were not under Kremlin control.
Public protest movements have erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate within the country.
Journalists and analysts do not always follow the Kremlin's line.
The Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of history.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and his protest movement has been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was shut down for being "extremist," and its members are either exiled or under investigation.
Nearly every day, journalists, media outlets, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agent" list — or worse, labeled as "unwelcome guests."
In the past year, Russia has slipped into a state of non-freedom, though not far removed, but very intense.
For example, in 2012, laws were enacted to designate foreign agents aimed at undermining or discrediting institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" who also receive funding from abroad.
But the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point where sharing tweets can now be grounds for being labeled as a foreign agent.
(The "unpopular" label can lead to complete prohibition.)
) This year alone, the list of foreign agents has grown to a record 101 entities.
The total of 359 includes 88 media-related institutions and individuals.
According to the Russian government, all these so-called "agents" must be listed because they "influence national politics."
But the core goal of news and propaganda work is naturally to influence politics.
And that is precisely the problem: while President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself as someone who will continue to control Russian politics for the foreseeable future, he sees criticism as a survival threat.
Despite all this silence and persecution, it is the Communist Party – an unlikely group – that has survived and become the only genuine opposition to the Kremlin.
This is largely due to Navalny’s “smart voting” strategy – encouraging people to support those candidates most likely to defeat the Kremlin-backed contenders – which proved particularly strong among the Communist Party in last month’s parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist candidates won 18.9% of the votes in the State Duma (parliament), compared to nearly 49.8% for the United Russia party backed by the Kremlin.
But the Communists refuse to accept this result, insisting that the vote was rigged.
Actually, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while United Russia should have received about 35%.
To many Russians, the Communists now seem more respectable than Putin.
But they are not the original Communists.
Not only do they not deny earthly pleasures; members of the party wear fur coats, are keen on traveling abroad, drive foreign cars, and use social media.
Some are millionaires – such as charming agricultural chief Pavel Grudinin (who was barred from participating in last month's election).
Despite being led by Genady Gennadievich Zhirinovsky, who is 77 years old, the party is increasingly influenced and supported by young members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko, for example.
This 36-year-old, known as "Red Navalny," criticized the poorly designed pension reform in 2018 severely.
Not long ago, when a regional minister suggested that Russians should be able to "eat better" on just 3,500 rubles (about $50) per month, Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove him wrong on his YouTube channel.
Despite threats to ban him from running, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in last month's State Duma elections.
Although he received support from Navalny’s smart voting system, he still lost to the United Russia candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently proposed a slogan for a protest against what he accused of “the state and government taking over” United Russia.
Then there is Anastasia Yudasoova, who is 43 years old.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains – and is increasingly – popular.
Thanks to the smart voting system, another rising star, elegant Yekaterina Engelicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the Communist Party's modernization reflects a nostalgia for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although their state was strict, it was still fair and benevolent.
In addition, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communists represent a predictable and consistent vision, under which one person's whims do not affect everyone.
It is precisely this logic that increasingly unites all opponents of the Kremlin: forming a unified front against United Russia, the party supported by Putin.
This is not unique to Russia.
In last month’s parliamentary election in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš – also known as Czech Donald Trump – failed to continue as prime minister because the opposition alliance put aside their ideological differences and formed a common front, with its leader Peter Fiala likely to lead a new government with another opposition alliance.
As Fiala put it, "People are fed up with populists," and they want "normal, competent, and respectable politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also present a unified electoral list and field a single candidate for prime minister in next year’s parliamentary elections.
Naturally, the Czech Republic still operates under a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join forces with the opposition.
Toppling Putin, however, will be much more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that there will be even more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party.
But these tactics also pose risks to the Kremlin.
The situation now is that the president claims Russian democracy has not disappeared and points to an "active opposition" as evidence, indicating at least a pretense of not wanting to push Russia towards near-totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia towards more tumultuous circumstances.
If the Kremlin, like it does with the Russian liberal opposition, repeatedly changes and enforces rules to drive the Communists underground, social explosion becomes more likely.
And if it decides not to continue being suppressed, the Russian Communists – yes, the Communists – could become a formidable political force.
